# Core conventions ‚Äî always on

## Source of truth for style and quality

Linting, formatting, and type checks are enforced by the repo's tooling,
not restated here. Consult these files instead of guessing:

- `pyproject.toml` ‚Äî ruff + ty + pytest configuration
- `.pre-commit-config.yaml` ‚Äî local commit gate (10 hooks)
- `.github/workflows/ci.yml` ‚Äî CI gate (wraps `just check`)
- `justfile` ‚Äî canonical commands

## Commands ‚Äî use `just`, not raw tools

- `just fmt` ‚Äî format
- `just lint` ‚Äî lint (use `just lint-fix` to auto-fix)
- `just type` ‚Äî type check (uses Astral's `ty`, not mypy)
- `just test` ‚Äî run tests
- `just pre-commit` ‚Äî run all 10 pre-commit hooks
- `just check` ‚Äî full quality gate (what CI runs)
- `just install-hooks` ‚Äî one-time setup after cloning

## Before claiming a change is done

1. `just check` passes locally (5 passed, 7 skipped is the expected baseline
   without an API key ‚Äî the skips are API-gated tests, not failures)
2. Any new public function has a test and a type-annotated signature
3. No new `print()` calls in library code ‚Äî use `logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)`
   (the `reporting/` package and `runner.py` are the allowed exceptions)
4. Diff looks like what you'd want in a PR review

## Branch and commit discipline

- Never commit directly to `main` ‚Äî a pre-commit hook blocks this. Escape
  only with `SKIP=no-commit-to-branch` and a good reason.
- Branches: `feat/<name>`, `fix/<name>`, `refactor/<name>`, `chore/<name>`,
  `docs/<name>`, `test/<name>`
- Conventional Commits format for messages
- One logical change per commit (or one squash-merged PR)
- After any update to local `main` (PR merge, `git pull`, fast-forward, etc.),
  immediately `git switch` to a parking branch ‚Äî by convention `scratch`,
  forked from the new `main` tip. This keeps the working copy off `main` so
  no edits or commits land there by accident. Create real work branches
  from `main`, not from `scratch`. If `scratch` is missing or stale,
  recreate it with `git switch -c scratch` from the current `main`.

## Ephemeral / scratch work

- Use `.scratch/` at repo root for throwaway files (git-ignored except
  `.gitkeep`)
- Never place exploratory scripts at repo root

## ty suppression syntax

`ty` uses different rule names than mypy. Suppress with
`# ty: ignore[<rule-name>]` ‚Äî where `<rule-name>` is the exact code from
the ty diagnostic header (e.g., `unknown-argument`,
`invalid-argument-type`). Bare `# type: ignore` also works but loses
specificity.

